incidents.name: A subset of users experiencing issue with Country code on outbound calls.

incident_updates.body: We are currently investigating reports where a subset of users are experiencing issue with Country code on outbound calls. Our engineers are currently investigating the impact and root cause. Zoom will provide updates as soon as there is more information to share.

The following new and updated IP subnet ranges will be deployed to Zoom resources starting no earlier than 30 days from the posting of this notice. We recommend that network administrators, with Zoom specific firewall or network rules, update their systems as soon as possible in preparation. 

An IP address (52.84.151.0/24) was announced for Zoom services in November 2022; however moving forward, this range is part of Zoom’s CDN network. Please update your firewall rules accordingly. 

Additionally, as Zoom continues to expand on its IPv6 footprint, we will be adding a new CIDR for meeting services.

New IPv6: 
2407:30C0::/32

A complete list of network firewall IP ranges for Zoom can be found on the Zoom Support site at: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/201362683

affected_components.name: Zoom Meetings - Zoom Conference Room Connector
Zoom Video Webinars - Zoom Video Webinars

incident_updates.body:
Zoom Phone users registered to the Europe (Amsterdam) data center will be automatically registered in an alternative datacenter starting at 10:00 PM CEST (1:00 PM Pacific on July 14th). During the maintenance window, a brief disconnection may be experienced and notifications may be missed. If you get disconnected, the system will attempt to reconnect you automatically. 

If you are a BYOC (Bring Your Own Carrier) customer, please ensure that your Session Border Controller (SBC) is configured with alternate routing to Europe (Frankfurt) data center in addition to the Europe (Amsterdam) data center. During the maintenance window, connectivity to Zoom’s Amsterdam data center will be blocked which will force calls from the Session Border Controller (SBC) to failover to Zoom’s Europe (Frankfurt) data center. Traffic will continue to be routed through the Zoom's Europe (Amsterdam) data center once the maintenance is completed.

For customers that use hardware phones, refer to this link for the devices support the alternative datacenter process as described above: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360029698771-Supported-desk-phone-features#h_01GNZ783VT6YXHES8NSXBA5M9A

scheduled_maintenances.name: Scheduled Zoom Software Quarterly Lifecycle Update (8/5/2023)

incident_updates.body:
Zoom will be enforcing a new minimum version of all our Zoom clients and plugins roughly 90 days from now on August 5, 2023. This affects the following products: 
- Zoom client for meetings (Windows, macOS, Linux, iOS, Android, Blackberry, and Intune)
- Zoom Rooms (including Zoom Room Controllers and companion whiteboards) 
- Zoom Phone Appliances
- VDI Client and Plugin
- Virtual Room Connector
- Meetings Connector
- Recording Connector
- Meetings SDK (Native and Web)
- Video SDK (Native and Web)

Please ensure your devices are updated to the latest version. 

For more information, such as specific versions we are enforcing, please see the Zoom Software Quarterly Lifecycle Policy support article: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360059429231 

To assist with checking the client versions on your account, refer to the Dashboard support article for more information: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360039656511#h_13ce9a73-91e5-4df6-9cb5-c815b1605cf5

scheduled_maintenances.name: End-of-life for JSON Web Token (JWT) app type

incident_updates.body:
As our other communications have indicated, Zoom is in the process of retiring the JSON Web Token (JWT) app type in the Zoom Marketplace. To effectively accommodate our users and partners, we are deploying this change in two phases: 
 - As of June 1, customers will no longer be able to create new JWT apps. 
 - As of September 1, authentication for tokens created using the JWT app type will stop functioning. 

To prevent disruption due to this change, Zoom recommends migrating to OAuth authentication as soon as possible. 

If you are an app developer still using JWT, please review the instructions on how to migrate your app or integration to OAuth: https://developers.zoom.us/docs/internal-apps/jwt-app-migration/

If you are an account owner or admin with a custom app used by your account, please review the instructions on how to check if your account is still making JWT requests: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360032447812#h_01GZFBMV8GQGGGYHAX1WVC8NQA

Some of Zoom’s Marketplace integrations have already been updated to support OAuth and require admins take a few additional steps to reconnect the integration with OAuth, instead of JWT: 
 - Azure SCIM: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/15053773250573
 - Salesforce for Zoom app: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/12362230591757
 - Epic integration: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/115002222603/#h_01GQ5YCN8SPMHNHWC846KE9VJP 
 - Epic FHIR integration: https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/4417529707789/#h_01GQ5VSVFY27VMWF8S2G2K6SYP 
 - Zoom Room APIs: https://developers.zoom.us/docs/api/rest/reference/zoom-api/methods/#tag/Zoom-Rooms

Note: If you are currently using a 3rd-party integration that uses JWT and is not listed above, we recommend reaching out to the developer for more information on their migration plan.
